The area

Address
Neighborhood: Ueno, Asakusa
Traces of the history and culture of the Edo (old Tokyo) era remain vividly in Ueno and Asakusa. Spacious Ueno Park is a great place to relax and visit a variety of different museums and galleries. At Ameyoko which starts in front of Ueno station, the grocery stores and clothing shops are crammed alongside fishmongers. It gets particularly busy at the end of the year, when many people go on shopping sprees. The town of Asakusa, developed around Sensoji temple, has many shops selling goods and clothing from old Japan, making it a great place for souvenir hunting. It's also known for various annual festivals, and the whole district gets involved with the huge Sanja Festival in May.

  • Amila Perera
    Gampaha, Sri Lanka506 contributions
    In a crowded area, hot and humid, the atmosphere buzzes with a mix of excitement and weariness as visitors navigate through throngs of people. As you make your way through this vibrant locale, it becomes essential to avoid the tourist traps that often lure unsuspecting travelers, such as the enticing offer to pay 100 yen for a fortune note, only to find that you might need to spend another 200 yen to negate the bad fortune that is all too common. Such practices can be frustrating and detract from the genuine experience of exploring the temple and its surrounding culture. However, amidst the hustle and bustle, there is a refreshing sense of cleanliness and order that stands out. The temple grounds are meticulously maintained, with lush greenery providing a stark contrast to the urban sprawl. The intricate architecture of the temple itself invites admiration, with its ornate carvings and vibrant colors telling stories of ancient traditions and spiritual significance. Visitors are encouraged to take their time, soaking in the serene environment, and perhaps engaging with local artisans or sampling traditional snacks from nearby vendors. This place, while bustling with tourists, also offers pockets of tranquility where one can reflect and appreciate the cultural heritage that thrives here. It’s worth venturing beyond the surface attractions to discover the deeper meanings and experiences that await those who seek them, making this journey not just about sightseeing, but about connecting with the spirit of the place.
    Review of: Senso-ji Temple

  • ThorwaldVikingAsgaar
    Winter Park, Florida215 contributions
    Sensō-ji is a Buddhist temple located in Asakusa. The colourful and popular temple features the Kaminarimon Gate (Thunder Gate) at the entrance. From this gate onwards, locals and tourists walk along Nakamise-Dori, a historic street lined with souvenir shops until they reach the second gate, the Hozomon. Outside the main hall and pagoda of Tokyo’s oldest temple, there is a fountain for washing hands, small stalls selling charms and rows of drawers for visitors to read their fortune for the day. The temple grounds offer ample photo opportunities around the trading hours of Nakamise-Dori when there are no crowds. If you decide to visit early in the morning, be wary of the shadows cast on some of the temple buildings from the surrounding skyscrapers. The main hall is open daily from 6am – 5pm, the temple grounds are always open and entrance is free.

  • SPAZIO_INFINITO
    Turin, Italy3,132 contributions
    Traveling around Tokyo we decided to visit the majestic Buddhist complex of Senso-ji. Located in Tokyo in the district of Asakusa (northeast), not far from the Skytree tower, easily accessible on foot and by public transport (the nearest subway station is Asakusa). The Senso-ji is one of the oldest and most important Buddhist temples in the city of Tokyo. It consists of numerous buildings made entirely of wood (painted in bright colors), enclosed within a green area with small Japanese-style gardens (very well maintained) and bodies of water with colorful carp. There was a very quiet and spiritual atmosphere thanks also to the aromas of incense burning around the temple. It is a very visited attraction, not only by tourists but also by the Japanese, I recommend stopping at Senso-ji during the week (early morning) if you want to take nice pictures in peace. Access to the temple is free, only the internal areas are reserved for the faithful. Upon our arrival a religious service was taking place with prayers by Buddhist monks (an emotional moment, very nice). Appropriate behavior and especially silence near the prayer area is required. Along the streets leading to the temple there are countless shops where you can buy souvenirs of all kinds. It takes about an hour to visit the temple complex. It was a pleasant visit, refreshing and spiritual. I would definitely recommend it.

    The vastness of this temple is amazing and includes not only the main hall, but also the surrounding land, including a small temple, gardens, cemetery and goldfish.     I had a great time at the Senso-ji Temple. Loved that despite its "tourist" status, this temple complex remains a model of Japanese tradition The temple, like the rest of the Asakusa area, suffered greatly from air raids during World War II. But the square around here has been rebuilt, and today it is noisy, fun, lots of tourists and even Japanese in kimonos who come to the temple to pray. I advise you to come here in the morning if you want peace and quiet, or in the evening if you are interested in trying street food and walking along the shopping street with traditional Japanese flashlights and a huge selection of souvenirs.

Historically rich site - lots to see and many food options

Oct 2025 • Friends
We had a guided tour led by Aya throughout the temple grounds. She gave us an excellent history lesson on the temple, how it was started, how Tokyo transformed over time and became the capital of Japan, and so much more. She was delightful.

The tour lasted about 2 hours. Unfortunately, we got a bit of a late start because our group did not connect with her right away. We arrived on time at the location that we were told but had to search for her.

The temple grounds are very crowded with lots of tourists. It was a challenge to get pictures because there was always someone in the background.

There were no lines or crowds to get a fortune, or to buy incense sticks. THere was a crowd to pray.

There are lots of things to see on the grounds so give yourself plenty of time to walk around.

If you have the chance, sign up for the Kimono and Matcha Tea Ceremony Experience. If you do, you will get dressed up in a kimono and can go back to the temple to take pictures in your kimono.
